author: Robert Dee

text: Hopefully this will be a good mix of the new Bond and the old Bond. I love the continuity and character driven focus of Craig's tenure, but seeing the white dinner jack, Nehru wearing Waltz, and gadget laden car makes me miss old James Bond films. At least the trailer makes SPECTRE look like a fun adventure, but at the same time not sacrificing character development. But the inclusion of the OHMSS theme makes me sad that David Arnold is not composing the score for SPECTRE. Newman's score for Skyfall was generic, but Arnold's has only gotten better with each film he was in (from Tomorrow Never Dies to QoS). I truly hope Newman will bring in a sense of continuity just like Arnold did for his QoS score, but I highly doubt it. Would have loved to have heard how Arnold would have connected CR, QoS, Skyfall, and SPECTRE together.

text: Looks totally epic. I love how the progression of the Craig Bond films have been, from Casino Royale to this. They've all been building to this, a reinvention of the classic Bond villains and motifs. The only thing I hope for is that things don't stray too far from the realistic and grounded Bond world that they've created. And with Mr. White back, I hope we finally get closure with how the Quantum organization connects or doesn't connect to SPECTRE. With Christoph Waltz saying that he is the reason behind all of Bond's "pain," I hope that works out to where he has been the big bad the whole time behind the scenes, going all the way back to Casino Royale, if not further back to the deaths of Bond's parents. That would too fucking cool.

text: Now I suddenly noticed something. Somewhere in the end-portion of the trailer there is a variation of the music from 'On Her Majesty's Secret Service'. And then I read this story and I recognize certain elements from that story actually: Crimelord (Mr White in this one, Marc-Ange Draco in the other one) helps Bond to track down the head of Spectre (Blofeld in the old one and Oberhauser in the new one) and because of that gets involved with the daughter of the crimelord (Madeleinne Swann in Spectre and Tracy in OHMSS). Those are just minor things, but maybe it's like a little hommage to one of the most underrated Bond-movies.

text: This may be blasphemous to say, but this actually looks way better than Skyfall. The best Bond films historically have him up against a nefarious organization rather than just one maniacal villian and his/her henchman (think From Russia With Love vs. The Man With The Golden Gun), and #24 has both an organization AND a villian & henchman. Can't wait to see Daniel Craig go toe-to-toe with Dave Bautista. While I can't say that Daniel is the best Bond (Connery still gets my vote), I do think when his run is over with the one film he has left that he'll have the best slate of movies ahead of Pierce Brosnan. How sick is that Aston Martin DB10 backfire by the way?!?

text: Arguably the best Bond cast ever assembled, but instead of replicating the sense of reality created by Casino Royale in an emotionally developed, cold hearted, ruthless agent who kills people with his bare hands, they seem to waste it all by continuing their revert back to the cheesy/overly ridiculous pre-Craig format of gadgets, stunts, explosions, and misplaced humour. CR was the best Bond film of all time, but it seems we're set to recommence the downward trend of class and quality, and it will continue until we're all the way back to Die Another Day. Shame, but i'm sure it will be a good easy watch as always.
I love it!! Can't wait to see it!!! :D

text: I'm a little sad to see we are going to have some more gadgets in this movie. I liked the films since Casino Royale without all the flash, it made Bond seem more real, more in danger. But, it is such staple part of the film history for the Bond series so I guess it was inevitable. At least I'm confident this actor and director will do it well. -- For anyone reading this who hasn't read the original novels written by Ian Fleming of James Bond, I really think everyone should give them a try. They are timeless and paint such a detailed picture of Bond ... not as an invincible super agent, but as a normal man working as a British spy after WWII, who's committed to his work, has an almost Sherlock Holmes way of taking in the details of people and situations, and enjoys women, drinking, eating, and smoking ... not because he's trying to be cool or even because he's a hedonist, but simply because he really does believe he will likely die at any moment and so he accepts that and resolves to enjoy such simple pleasures whenever possible.

text: Hear that thunder? It may have scared the living daylights out of you and left you shaken and stirred, but take solace; the sky isn't falling, and it wasn't some specter! It's just the latest killer view of Her Majesty's spy we all love, for your golden eyes only. James Bond returns as a secret agent man with a gun and a license to kill, in another gem of a romp royale from EON with love, that studio with the golden touch. Mayhem with a capital M, that you can really sink your jaws into!  Tomorrow can't come soon enough, but we'll have to live with that, and let another moon pass and another day die. In the meantime, grab Moore 007 from the Sellers on Daniel Craigslist. Then by George Lazenby and the Austin Powers that be, take a day off your odd job, get a house sitter for your eight cats, and Pierce your way through the queue. Because it's that Tim-o-thy year for a film that will have you singing like a Connery with praise. If your doctor says no, well never say never because you only live once!

Thousands of Palmyra‚Äôs residents fled but many are still living within the city walls, while the UN human rights office in Geneva said it had received reports of Syrian government forces preventing people from leaving until they retreated from the city.  TEENS ACROSS THE COUNTRY ARE CONJURING UP DEMONS ON TWITTER: A game that purports to invoke a Mexican demon ‚Äì known as ‚ÄúCharlie, Charlie‚Äù and considered to be a simplified version of the Ouija board ‚Äì has gone viral on social media among young people, prompting one exorcist to warn of its dangers. The game, which has gained significant traction online in recent days, involves a pair of pencils or pens, a sheet of paper, and the invocation of a spirit named ‚ÄúCharlie.‚Äù Scores of short video clips, posted mostly by teens, show players shrieking and running out of view when the pencil apparently moves on its own and points to a ‚Äúyes‚Äù or a ‚Äúno‚Äù after they say a phrase inviting the demon. text: I see a lot of Humour (Daniel Craig doing One Liners!? will miracles never cease?, In all seriousness however, I think this is actually¬†the first time I have actually¬†heard him crack a Joke in the Films, I know he Cracked a lot off in "Bloodstone"...but then¬†Rumor has it that Game was written¬†with Pierce in mind¬†rather than Daniel, so it¬†proabably does¬†not count. Shame the Story got completely¬†messed up sometime in Development as well..and that it was just a cheap and nasty Uncharted clone rather than a Proper Third Person Shooter...), Gadgets (finally, its been too long)!, and Action (With Practical Effects!? what Sourcery is this?)! in this trailer? Does this mean we are Finally¬†going to get a Proper Spy Movie again¬†this time?  Or are we in for¬†yet another boring, depressive, Emotional Drama like the last¬†Three Films?¬†I was so disgusted with Skyfall, for¬†example, that¬†I ended up walking out part way through!¬†(I have never done that before,¬†I even watched "Die Another Day" to the end!)¬†For Me,¬†Bond¬†just is not Bond in the Recent Films, and was even Worse in Skyfall, as, in my eyes, He¬†was just a Traitorous, emotionally wrecked, Failure! in that film (He failed, every. single, objective), He wasn't even a Man anymore. It got to the point, before¬†I walked out,¬†I was feeling that even¬†Sterling Archer probably would have done a more competent Job!!... I really¬†do Not want to see another James Bond Film of that ilk Again,¬†Three is Three too many for my Tastes!  007, in my opinion¬†is supposed to be¬†a Spy Movie, not an Emotional Drama. Please Stop copying the Bourne (Matt Damon era..the 1988 TV one with Richard Chamberlain was¬†Awesome, as¬†was "Legacy" with Jeremy Renner, Those 2 are Spy Movies¬†IMO)¬†and Kindly start copying Kingsman (at least its more¬†'60s inspired¬†elements), Mission Impossible (4¬†especially) and the very True to the¬†Roots ¬†"Man From UNCLE" reboot! The 007 Franchise has only just been kept ticking over for me since the Dire "Die Another Day" (which felt more like a Videogame than the Downright Awesome "Nightfire"...which actually¬†was a Videogame!)¬†with the Games¬†(even if I have hated the gameplay of all the Activision era titles, I¬†Grew Up as a Gamer¬†during the '90's (PC and¬†Consoles at the same time, a rare breed)¬†,I have¬†got¬†very old school tastes as a result..modern, "casual", gameplay just does not appeal to Me), as Bond had a¬†more old school, less emotional, more..."Bond" personality in them.¬†With the Games¬†seemingly Killed off now, if the next Movie is yet another Emotional-Drama, than the Entire Franchise is just Dead to Me.  This trailer, thankfully, Looks like¬†the Bond Films are thankfully¬†going down the MI4/Kingsman (but 12A rather than 18) /UNCLE style "Classic Spy Movie" direction...i Just hope the Film lives up to that Promise¬†. As I am going to be¬†pretty Upset¬†if they get my hopes of one last "real" Bond film up like this and it turns out to be yet¬†another Bourne Inspired Emotional- Drama.¬†  Please! No "Personal Issues", No "Emotional Wreck" rubbish, No "Doubts", No¬†"Main Bond Girl who is Bonds Equal"¬†again¬†(we have had¬†that¬†one since Liscence to Kill, and I am¬†personally Sick of it! for Me the Hugely Intelligent yet¬†Sweet, Timid, Damsely (and very possibly Autistic, she shows a Lot of Signs of Aspergers)¬†version¬†of Natalya from "Goldeneye:Reloaded" was the best Bond Girl in Years! She was certainly¬†the best bit of that cheap and nasty "Cry On Doody" copy!), no Failed Objectives. No Balderdash!. Just Lots of Cool Cars, lots of Cool Gadgets, plenty of¬†attractive Women, tonnes of one liners,¬†a successful mission, and a 100+ Mook¬†Bodycount ,or this franchise really is Dead to Me. A Franchise¬†I¬†have followed since¬†I was 4.  I really don't¬†want that to have to classify it as Dead to Me!

text: Isn't this the last time Daniel Craig's playing Bond? I must admit, when he started I was very dubious. Having grown up in the hay-day of Roger Moore as Bond, he represented 007 for me. There hasn't, frankly, been a bad Bond but after seeing Daniel Craig smash it I'll be unhappy to see him wave it away (if this is his last standing). He exceeded my expectations and really smashed it home, very consistently too, I might add.¬† ¬†That being said, who better to share his last hurrah with then Christoph Waltz? That man's a goddamn genius on set, there's not been a role I've seen that he's been in that hasn't been excellent, even during films that were overall lackluster (I.E. Carnage), he still did a stellar onscreen job. Genuinely can't say I've looked forward to a villain's appearance more, Javier Bardem was exquisite, but I think Waltz will top it.¬† ¬†Still, I wonder where Bond will go after this? If this is Daniel Craig's sign off on the Bond role, I'm anxious to see who'll take up the mantle of one of my favourite film franchises. I've heard that dozens of big time, Hollywood heavy hitters are keen on the role and I'd be delighted to see a number of them take on the role, especially Tom Hardy, Damian Lewis, Micheal Fassbender, Tom Hiddleston, Guy Pearce, Henry Cavil and Idris Elba all be potential candidates, but that's just a handful of the lot who've shown major interest. I'd be bucking for Jason Statham but I'm not sure he's got enough of the "casual" side before the shooting starts and the car chases begin, though he can definitely pull off the wit. More worrying still is where they'll pull the next villain from. Over the last few films I believe we've seen the pinnacle of them, (not to say there haven't been some excellent performances and memorable villains prior to all this) and they'll be tough acts to improve on.¬† ¬†Still, Daniel Craig, you absolutely rocked this roll and I can't wait to see Spectre in all its glory, really looking forward!

I mean for instance they didn't do a wide shot as the plane was crashing, and the Camera work needs to be good like in Casino Royale, remember that great wide shot of the DB9 toppling over and spinning and crashing when Bond swerved out of the way in order to not hit the girl, that was GREAT! But just as I looked at the few shots of the crashes in the trailer I'm starting to wonder whether they've done an as gooder job as the film Casino Royale.

text: OK, my take is that there will never be another Connery - Bond, we all need to get past that.¬† I have accepted Craig in the role, partly because his timing is masterful in delivering subtle irreverence with with cutting edged dry English humor that has been one of the Bond trademarks.¬† The other reason I have accepted him is that I have reset the character in my head to be a code name and field number where the actual identity is an MI6 best kept secret (if there are any).¬† The revamp of staff and characters was almost too much to bare in Skyfall, but I'm settling in with the new "Q" and the RIP "M".¬† I always had a thing for her taste for Scotch, neat.¬† She was one tough broad!¬† I am looking forward to the Spectre reboot.¬† I just know Christoph Waltz will be someone I love to hate.¬† Back to Bond; How do you top jumping onto an out of control train which has just been shot to hell and eaten by a 100 ton digger?¬† By straightening your thrashed suit and tie while ratcheting your neck back into place from the whiplash you just got getting there!¬† That's the kind of sharp edged subtlety I love about the Daniel Craig character.¬† All the Bonds had character and charm (well, maybe not Dalton).¬† I would enjoy seeing them do something together on the side, not necessarily as a mainstream Bond but maybe as something where a villian got that secret list of all the operatives' real names and was taking them out one-by-one.¬† I think it would be cool to see them overlapping wit, charm, audacity, and skills; even as geriatrics to the new guys.¬† That done with a reasonable budget and good direction, like maybe John Woo, could play out like a serious expendables, only from over the pond.¬† Might be a hoot!

text: As a fan of the James Bond films for most of my life - I saw Dr No on its initial release - I am disgusted that the films are now embarrassed by their own legacy. The new Bond films have distanced themselves from James Bond as we knew him for forty years.¬†  All you young fans have no idea that you have bought into a different franchise with the Bond name attached and I feel sorry for you all.¬†  I really hope that they revert to making Bond films again soon so you can all understand what you have been missing on the big screen.

I miss this in the newest Bond-films :-/ Casino Royale have it, but it last for 3 seconds, Quantum of Solace (10 seconds), and Skyfall every now and then, but in the wrong time (except for the Aston Martin scene...) Give me back the BOND MUSIC in Spectre!!! Please ;-)

text: If you notice, from 1:44 to 1:53 the music they play is a variation of the theme song from On Her Majesty's Secret Service. I feel like this film is channeling that one a lot. It also took place in Switzerland, which we see a lot of in this movie. OHMSS was the best book of the Spectre trilogy, and the movie was an unappreciated gem of the series, which was also the only Bond film that followed the book almost to the word. I also kind of feel like it was the most important one of the trilogy. I love how Daniel Craig's movies conjure up memories of the literary Bond to me.

text: What astounds me is the level of promotion for the "Bond" franchise at the moment, just as we had coming towards the release of the last Bond movie. The Sunday Times is the greatest offender. We get articles on Ian Fleming, articles on who influenced the creation of the Bond characters, articles on Bond's Austin Martin car. Even the Style section managed a cover story on Bond star Naomie Harris entitled "Moneypenny's Mission". Does Rupert Murdock have shares in the franchise or is he or his paper being paid directly for such "promotion". When I buy the Sunday Times I feel I'm a target.

text: Whenever I see the trailer for Specter, I am reminded of these spy films have completely run out of ideas, whether it be James Bond, Mission Impossible, Bourne, or whatever.   It is sort of like watching World Wrestling Entertainment priming us for the next PPV the same way every time. *No, this time it is even more personal for Bond. No, THIS villain was behind everything, forget the last. This time Bond is even more on the run than before. This time his agency REALLY hates him.*  "It was me, James."  *yawn*  These franchises are so intent on outdoing each other by making it more 'personal', by making the new villain be the most hated baddie, by having their agencies not side with them... that they are parodying themselves.  Just like cartoonish action sequences were overly indulged in by the later Pierce Brosnan films, the Daniel Craig films are tapping the 'gritty' tropes dry.

text: As somebody who ranks Daniel Craig as the WORST of the Bonds hands down (sorry for those of you get hurt feelings from that due to thin skin), I have to say that this particular trailer (not the other Spectre trailers, though) actually give me a bit of hope for this one.  I will actually go see it with an open mind thanks to whoever edited this particular trailer.  I thought Casino Royale was a great Bond film (nowhere near the best, not even close, but still very, very good; then again, I'm not a Dark Knight fan and those who like Craig's films seem to be hardcore Dark Knight nut swingers so it's no wonder we differ in opinion on Craig's Bond films for the most part).  Unfortunatley, I have grown to despise Craig in the role since his very promising first outing.  He's simply a one note Bond and a very uninteresting one at that.  He lacks so much that makes Bond an interesting character, the most obvious being wit and ingenuity (Craig's Bond is just a brooding hulk who simply reacts instead of THINKING and using quick wit and cleverness which is what made Bond stand out from other action heroes) and of course a strong and likable personality (Craig's a zombie Bond).  Those who say he's more like what a real spy would be are off their rockers.  A real spy would fit in and be totally inconspicuous with nobody even knowing he was there or what he did.  He'd either have to be so nondescript that nobody would notice him or he'd have a friendly personality where everybody liked him and wouldn't think of him as an espionage expert.  Craig's Bond is a brooding hulk with anger management and mommy issues.  He'd stand out like a sore thumb on any security guard's radar.  Apart from disliking Craig as Bond, the films themselves have been terrible as far as plot, storytelling, suspense, and action executiion.  I haven't felt on the edge of my seat in a Bond film since Craig got hit in the nuts over and over again in Casino.  They came close in Skyfall with Bond hanging from an elevator, but they cheated the end of the scene by not showing how he got to safety and simply cutting to him brushing himself off while on safe ground (that was a major missed opportunity).  Maybe that's what today's PC emo audiences like, just straight ahead forward action like the demo of a video game, but this old school movie fan likes "how's he gonna get out of this seemingly impossible situation" scenarios and those have been sadly lacking during Craig's era.  Still, this trailer seems to be mixing a lot of the old (almost to the point of rip-off) with the new "melodrama" that modern fans jizz over.  This mixture just might make for a film that's close to Casino Royale.  That one had too much past Bond backlash for my tastes, but was faithful to the story overall which is why it succeeded (plus it had great locales and felt fresh at the time).  This one seems to embrace some of the old while maintaining much of the new which could be wise.  Still, what has Barbara Broccoli got against casting drop dead gorgeous women in the latest Bond films.  It's ragged and weary sticks versus our old bombshells, another HUGE minus in direction.  I don't think I'll be back onboard the Bond train in full until they go back to embracing Bond as the character he's been made out to be for decades with great success (I like every single Bond actor apart from Craig whom I liked in Casino Royale but who brings nothing to the role now; that's a sure sign that something is wrong with him not the viewer since none of the other actors were clones of each other yet they were all unequivocally James Bond and not just another tough guy action hero).  Yeah, sod on Craig's Bond, but fingers crossed that Spectre at least gets back to Casino Royale territory as far as story and locales go.

text: I've seen this movie today. Excellent. I'm just warning you that this comment is a spoiler alert. Only read it if  you've already seen the movie. So the opening scene was brilliant. And then Dave Bautista shows up in a meeting, severely injuring a member and then someone else comes in and sights Bond in the crowd above them and chases after him with pistols and he makes a getaway with his Aston Martin car when suddenly Dave Bautista shows up in his car and they have a chase right beside the London river and Bond uses a flamethrower hidden inside his car and spots a ramp and ejected his seat before parachuting down safely. Then he travels to Austria and finds a house in the middle of nowhere. He finds a mirror which has a secret basement behind it and finds an old man. Bond tries to make a deal with him to protect his daughter no matter what, but it doesn't end up very good. The man sadly commits suicide. Then Bond finds a plane and flies it to the late man's daughter's work building. Suddenly, Dave Bautista shows up and kidnaps her and Bond gets his plane and chases Dave Bautista's vehicle. It ends with explosive action and Bond takes the girl to North Africa hoping she'll be safe. They book a train to go on (I don't know where though!) but suddenly, and I mean suddenly, Dave Bautista shows up yet again but this time he fights Bond and the girl but especially Bond! He tries to throw Bond out of the train but fails when Bond successfully throws Dave Bautista out. But then I think they got kicked out the train so they were waiting for another train to swing by. Then they sighted a very old car driving in there direction. The polite driver let them in and took them to a base in a meteor crater. The men took them to a strange building which had a meteor placed in side it. It was said to be the exact meteorite that created the crater. Then they take Bond and the girl to a control room. They play the video of the girl's father committing  suicide. Bond tells the girl to look at him because the footage was violent, graphic and scary. Then because of that, they hit Bond with a gun before knocking him out. Bond wakes in a chair. The man who is the leader of the company, has a small drill inside the chair which he used to drill his forehead, neck and very nearly his eyeballs. But before that nearly occurred, Bond told the girl to come near him and he gave the girl a bomb which she used to injure about 4 people. They they make a getaway with an pulse rifle and a submachine gun which he at least killed 6 people. He also used a pistol to blow up an explosive object which caused a massive, and this time I mean massive, explosion. When they thought it was finished, it ignited another bomb which caused another big explosion. Then they travel back to London when they go for a drive. But suddenly, another villain appears and crashes Bond's car. The villains kidnap Bond when taking him to a building when outside, Bond grabs a gun and shoots the villains before snapping his handcuffs. Then he goes on a rampage killing all the villains when he comes across a villain with a forcefield in front of him. When he gets closer to the forcefield, he realises it was a villain that he encountered before, (I think although I don't know who!) He has a bloody scar on his eye and that eye is blinded. He sets up a bomb that will demolish the whole building in 300 seconds.  Bond hears yelling in the walls when he finds out they kidnapped the girl! She gets out and trusts Bond to fall on a net which was √† stunt btw and then they get a speedboat to run away in while the villain gets a helicopter. They both survive the demolition but suddenly Bond shoots the helicopter which caused it to crash. Bond was about to shoot him but he told him that he's got other things to do. That is the film Spectre my friends.

text: I really liked this one, even though I was thwarted by the previews showing the main villain, which seems ridiculous for a trailer to do, unless the villain isn't already know. The lurking behind the shadows really creates a special imagery that can bring audiences to the theater rather than already knowing what to expect. What I didn't expect from this movie was the amazing artistic scenes that really fed some emotional charisma. The cultural feel of the James Bond movies has always carried itself well. The opening scene and the day of the dead celebration really showcased a fun experience outside of Bond itself, still keeping with the secrecy elements, and the masquerade behind the masks. The scenes of Rome were also well done especially where even a small glimpse of Monica Bellucci, her scene was pivotal in a cinematographic sense which really captured well a strong feeling of strange within this society that is silent but yet coming together in around the columns of Rome. The lighting of the walking scene as well previously the funeral scene with the slow string build up of feeling that aroused a tension of the two main characters as well bellucci's almost Contrapossto singularity. The viewers sense of awe being entangled with many amazing touches. This is all very interesting to me in that sense.   The action scenes especially the fighting scenes were done well in the sense that it was a brutal finish which didn't entertain James Bond magic too much, but a rugged throw down which was logically fit to show how it could be done. That being said the escape scene disappointed me a bit in that sense which didn't flow through the same continuity of how to actually escape but ended up being more a James Bond magical get away. All in all this was a really awesome film, but it's not without it's questions and disappointments, which I could mention more, only you should check it out for yourself. I could easily watch this movie again.

text: honestly, i don't even know why i keep watching these bond movies. take 'spectre' for example ~ all style, no substance. folks, please recognize this plot is entirely formulaic and basically pretty much hack work, all hidden in great production values.  beyond that, i find these movies pretty boring. yes, i said it: bond movies are boring with a couple of interesting scenes and a few ridiculous action bits that, sadly, fail to impress. here, the bond character goes nowhere and winds up being everything i make fun of in revenge-action flicks, where the hero kills a thousand people without blinking in a quest to reach the antagonist, gets the baddie in his sights and *doesn't* kill the incredibly dangerous psychopath because 'character arc.'   there are quite a few bits in this movie that just doesn't make sense to me. bond just walks into a supposedly secure spectre meeting just by showing a ring? really? that's it? i find it dubious logic that the 00 programme would be scrapped for being a relic of the past when in real life experienced field agents are still very much needed. the idea that we can do everything by drone and surveillance is ludicrous even by spy movie standards. the girl has little reason to fall in love with bond, but does anyway because of... reasons. i guess we're to believe that bond has left the agency because he likes some chick he met a couple of days hence? i could go on, but there's no point.  bottom line for me here is that great production values are hiding an entirely generic plot and characters. a few bright spots can't redeem an overall dull flick.
